  "local_port": 48494,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What do we call video with words on it?",
  "response": "Videos that incorporate words or text can be referred to by several different terms, depending on how the text is used and the purpose it serves. Here are some common terms:\n\n1. **Text Overlay Videos**:\n   - **Definition**: These are videos where text is superimposed over the visual content. The text can provide additional information, emphasize points, or convey messages without relying solely on spoken words.\n   - **Use Cases**: Educational tutorials, marketing videos, social media content.\n\n2. **Subtitled Videos**:\n   - **Definition**: Subtitles are textual representations of the spoken dialogue in a video, usually placed at the bottom of the screen.\n   - **Use Cases**: Foreign films, accessibility for hearing-impaired viewers, translating dialogue for a broader audience.\n\n3. **Captioned Videos**:\n   - **Definition**: Similar to subtitles, captions provide a text version of the dialogue and may include descriptions of sounds, music, and other audio elements for accessibility purposes.\n   - **Use Cases**: Educational content, public service announcements, online streaming platforms to comply with accessibility standards.\n\n4. **Kinetic Typography Videos**:\n   - **Definition**: These videos use animated text to convey ideas or emotions dynamically. The movement, color, and style of the text are integral to the visual storytelling.\n   - **Use Cases**: Music videos, advertisements, explainer videos.\n\n5. **Lyric Videos**:\n   - **Definition**: A specific type of video that displays the lyrics of a song in sync with the music. The text is often creatively animated to enhance the listening experience.\n   - **Use Cases**: Music promotion, fan engagement, artist discographies.\n\n6. **Title Sequences or Intro Videos**:\n   - **Definition**: These are videos that feature titles, usually at the beginning of a film, TV show, or online content, often incorporating text in a stylized format.\n   - **Use Cases**: Movie introductions, TV show openings, branded content intros.\n\n7. **Infographics Videos**:\n   - **Definition**: Videos that combine visual data representations with text to explain complex information clearly and engagingly.\n   - **Use Cases**: Educational content, data presentations, corporate communication.\n\n**Choosing the Right Term**:\nThe appropriate term depends on the context and purpose of the video:\n- If the text is primarily for translating or transcribing dialogue, \"subtitled\" or \"captioned\" are appropriate.\n- If the text is a central element of the visual design and animated, \"kinetic typography\" might be the best term.\n- For videos showcasing song lyrics, \"lyric video\" is most accurate.\n- For general purposes where text complements the visuals without a specific function, \"text overlay\" is suitable.\n\nUnderstanding the specific role that text plays in your video will help you choose the most accurate term.",
